#: ../../../advanced/pool.rst:437
msgid "Integration with SQLAlchemy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pool.rst:441
msgid ""
"If you want to use SQLAlchemy__ with psycopg's connection pool you can use "
"the SQLAlchemy's NullPool__ feature, using the pool's `~ConnectionPool."
"getconn` as `!creator` function. However, SQLAlchemy expects that calling "
"`~psycopg.Connection.close()` on the connection will return the connection "
"to the pool, which is not Psycopg's default behaviour."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pool.rst:450
msgid ""
"Since `!psycopg_pool` version 3.3, the `!close_returns` parameter of the "
"pool allows to change this behaviour, telling its connections to return to "
"the pool, instead of closing, when `!close()` is called."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pool.rst:454
msgid "For example, the initialization in an async application may look like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pool.rst:456
msgid ""
"import psycopg_pool\n"
"import sqlalchemy.pool\n"
"import sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio\n"
"\n"
"db_url = \"postgresql://postgres:postgres@hostname:port/database\"\n"
"\n"
"async def main():\n"
"    # Create and open a Psycopg pool\n"
"    pgpool = psycopg_pool.AsyncConnectionPool(\n"
"        conninfo=db_url, open=False, close_returns=True\n"
"    )\n"
"    await mypool.open()\n"
"\n"
"    # Create a SQLAlchemy engine using the pool just created\n"
"    engine = sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio.create_async_engine(\n"
"        url=\"postgresql+psycopg://\",\n"
"        poolclass=sqlalchemy.pool.NullPool,\n"
"        async_creator=pgpool.getconn,\n"
"    )\n"
"\n"
"    # Use the `engine` in the rest of your application.\n"
"    await run_my_app(engine)\n"
"\n"
"if __name__ == \"__main__\":\n"
"    asyncio.run(main())"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pool.rst:484
msgid ""
"If you want to integrate the Psycopg pool with SQLAlchemy using a `!"
"psycopg_pool` version older than 3.3, you will need to create a subclass of "
"the `~psycopg.Connection` or `~psycopg.AsyncConnection` class, overriding "
"the `!close()` method, with an implementation similar to the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pool.rst:489
msgid ""
"class MyAsyncConnection(psycopg.AsyncConnection):\n"
"    # If you need to subclass a sync connection, just drop the\n"
"    # 'async' and 'await' keywords from this example.\n"
"    async def close(self) -> None:\n"
"        if pool := getattr(self, \"_pool\", None):\n"
"            # Connection currently checked out from the pool.\n"
"            # Instead of closing it, return it to the pool.\n"
"            await pool.putconn(self)\n"
"        else:\n"
"            # Connection not part of any pool, or currently into the pool.\n"
"            # Close the connection for real.\n"
"            await super().close()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pool.rst:504
msgid ""
"Using a connection implementing this method you will not need to specify `!"
"close_returns` in the pool constructor, but just `!connection_class`; the "
"example above would be modified as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pool.rst:508
msgid ""
"pgpool = psycopg_pool.AsyncConnectionPool(\n"
"    conninfo=db_url, open=False, connection_class=MyAsyncConnection\n"
")"
msgstr ""
